<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Archegos</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One important thing that investment ba=
nks do is lend money to hedge funds to buy stocks. This is risky: If the st=
ocks go down, the hedge fund=C2=A0might not repay the loans, and then the b=
ank might lose money. So a central question of risk management is whether=
=C2=A0the hedge fund has posted enough collateral =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, t=
hat the stocks it owns are worth significantly more than the money the bank=
 has loaned it, so that if the stocks go down=C2=A0the bank will not lose m=
oney.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One aspect of this question is: What =
is the right amount of collateral? This question can be reduced to question=
s like: How much will the stocks go down in a plausible worst case? How qui=
ckly can we sell the stocks, and how much more will they go down due to our=
 selling? You can look at numbers about historical and implied volatility a=
nd=C2=A0correlations of the stocks in the portfolio, you can compare the po=
sition sizes to the stocks=E2=80=99 daily volumes, you can plug these thing=
s into=C2=A0formulas and run scenario analyses, you can get some numbers. T=
hese are well-known problems that have received a great deal of academic, r=
egulatory and practitioner attention, and you can read papers and books abo=
ut the best practices for figuring out the right amount of collateral.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another, underrated aspect of the question =
is: Once you know the right amount of collateral, and you call up the hedge=
 fund to tell it to post more collateral, and the hedge fund says =E2=80=9C=
I=E2=80=99m busy today let=E2=80=99s talk tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and you call t=
hem tomorrow and they say =E2=80=9Chey this week got away from me but send =
me an email,=E2=80=9D and you send them an email summarizing your collatera=
l demand and call them next week and they say =E2=80=9Coh I haven=E2=80=99t=
 had a chance to look at your email yet but I will very soon,=E2=80=9D and =
meanwhile the right amount of collateral keeps ticking up =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wh=
at do you do about that? There is a=C2=A0theoretical=C2=A0and contractual=
=C2=A0answer, which is, if the client doesn=E2=80=99t post the collateral y=
ou want then you terminate the swap, but you are a person and the hedge fun=
d does sound really busy and surely it can=E2=80=99t hurt to talk to them t=
omorrow? Plus if you terminate the swap you lose their business, and your w=
hole job is about doing more business.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=
=E2=80=99s an absolutely majestic paragraph about investment bank risk mana=
gement:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On February 19, 2021, t=
he PSR analyst sent a dynamic margining proposal to the Head of PSR for int=
ernal review, noting that he had made the terms =E2=80=9Cabout as tight=E2=
=80=9D as possible, yielding an average margin of 16.74% if applied to Arch=
egos=E2=80=99s existing swaps portfolio and leading to a day-one step up of=
 approximately $1.27 billion in additional margin. This was less than half =
of the additional initial margin that would have been required if Archegos=
=E2=80=99s Prime Brokerage dynamic margining rules were applied to Archegos=
=E2=80=99s swaps portfolio.On February 23, 2021, the PSR analyst covering A=
rchegos reached out to Archegos=E2=80=99s Accounting Manager and asked to s=
peak about dynamic margining. Archegos=E2=80=99s Accounting Manager said he=
 would not have time that day, but could speak the next day. The following =
day, he again put off the discussion, but agreed to review the proposed fra=
mework, which PSR sent over that day. Archegos did not respond to the propo=
sal and, a week-and-a-half later, on March 4, 2021, the PSR analyst followe=
d up to ask whether Archegos =E2=80=9Chad any thoughts on the proposal.=E2=
=80=9D His contact at Archegos said he =E2=80=9Chadn=E2=80=99t had a chance=
 to take a look yet,=E2=80=9D but was hoping to look =E2=80=9Ctoday or tomo=
rrow.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first few s=
entences there are about technical questions of the right amount of collate=
ral, etc. But once you have the right amount, you call the client. And the =
client is busy! And then what?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In thi=
s particular case the answer to =E2=80=9Cand then what=E2=80=9D is that, a =
couple of weeks later, the stocks that Archegos Capital Management owned we=
nt down a lot, and it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/24592602.260173/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3=
dhcmQtZm9yLWJhbmtz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2281a781" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> did not have enough money</a> =
to pay back its loans from=C2=A0Credit Suisse Group AG (whose Prime Service=
