</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in February, Nikola Corp., the el=
ectric-truck company that went public last year by merging with a special p=
urpose acquisition company, released a report by its own lawyers finding th=
at its founder had lied about some stuff. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/24592602.260173/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjYvc3RhcnR1cHMtc29tZXRpbWVzLXN0cmV0Y2gt=
dGhlLXRydXRo/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB826a721e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> summarized the report</a> like this:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did Nikola=E2=80=99s founder l=
ie about whether Nikola had produced a zero-emissions truck? Yes, say Nikol=
a=E2=80=99s own lawyers in Nikola=E2=80=99s own annual report to the U.S. S=
ecurities and Exchange Commission. Did he lie about whether the truck worke=
d? Yes. Did he lie when he said that all the major components for the truck=
 were made in-house? Yes. Did he lie when he said that trucks were coming o=
ff the assembly line? Of course. Did Nikola produce a video to make it seem=
 like the truck could be driven, when in fact it was only moving because it=
 was rolling down a hill? Yes, that is also a real thing that this company =
really did.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But was the company =E2=80=9Can=
 =E2=80=98intricate=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98massive fraud=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D? N=
o, no, what are you talking about, not a fraud at all.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My point was that startups, in their early stages,=
 sometimes say things that aren't quite true in order to encourage a shared=
 sense of belief by employees and investors, and that if this works it can =
sort of be bootstrapped into reality. If Nikola=E2=80=99s founder lied abou=
t its trucks early on, in order to raise funding to make those trucks real,=
 then, as I put it, =E2=80=9Cthat's not a =E2=80=98massive fraud,=E2=80=99 =
that=E2=80=99s just, like, startups, man.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">This is a better defense for=C2=A0<em>Nikola=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94 a =
continuing company that is trying to make trucks with all that money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0than it is for that=C2=A0<em>founder</em>, though. If he lied to i=
nvestors, that=E2=80=99s not great, even if later everything more or less c=
omes true. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2459260=
2.260173/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMj=
kvbmlrb2xhLWZvdW5kZXItY2hhcmdlZC1mb3ItYWxsZWdlZGx5LW1pc2xlYWRpbmctaW52ZXN0b=
